<h2>
    Licensing, Regulations &amp; Conservation Tips
</h2>
<h3>
    Oregon Fishing Licenses
</h3>
<p>
    You’ll need an Oregon angling license for anyone over age 12. Buy online via ODFW's site or in local stores.
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Free Fishing Weekends:</strong> No license needed – usually June and November
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    Catch-and-Release &amp; Advisories
</h3>
<p>
    Respect local advisories on river pollution, especially in urban stretches like the Willamette. Follow these tips:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        Use barbless hooks
    </li>
    <li>
        Keep fish wet
    </li>
    <li>
        Limit handling time
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Frequently Asked Questions
</h2>
<p>
    <strong>1. What’s the closest trout fishing spot to downtown Portland?</strong><br>
    Bethany Pond and Salish Ponds are among the closest, ideal for quick trips with decent catches.
</p>
<p>
    <strong>2. Do I need a fishing license for catch-and-release trout fishing?</strong><br>
    Yes. A license is required even if you're not keeping your catch, unless it's a Free Fishing Weekend.
</p>
<p>
    <strong>3. When is the best time of year to fish for trout near Portland?</strong><br>
    Spring through early fall is best, with optimal conditions in May–June and September.
</p>
<p>
    <strong>4. What types of trout can I catch around Portland?</strong><br>
    Primarily <strong>rainbow</strong>, <strong>cutthroat</strong>, and occasionally <strong>brook</strong> and <strong>bull trout</strong> in higher elevation areas.
</p>
<p>
    <strong>5. Are there guided trout fishing trips near Portland?</strong><br>
    Yes. Several outfitters in Portland and Sandy offer guided day trips on the Clackamas, Sandy, and Deschutes Rivers.
</p>
<p>
    <strong>6. Can I fish for trout in the rain?</strong><br>
    Absolutely. Trout often feed more actively during light rain, especially in streams and rivers.
</p>
<h2>
    Conclusion
</h2>
<p>
    The <strong>best trout fishing spots near Portland, Oregon</strong> cater to all experience levels—from urban lakes to remote mountain streams. Whether you're casting from the banks of Trillium Lake or nymphing in Eagle Creek, there's no shortage of rewarding experiences just a short drive from the city. Be sure to gear up responsibly, respect local regulations, and most importantly, enjoy the journey.
</p>

